      "content": "A bad capacitor can definitely cause a humming sound, especially if it's failing and not properly regulating the electrical current to the fan motor. If you've heard a loud pop, that could be a sign that the capacitor has blown. To check if the capacitor is blown, you can use a multimeter to test its voltage. If the voltage is significantly lower than the rated voltage, or if you get an open circuit reading, then the capacitor is likely blown and needs to be replaced. However, be careful when working with electrical components, and if you're not comfortable doing it yourself, it's best to call a professional. Just remember, working with electrical components can be dangerous, so always take proper precautions. And if you're feeling adventurous, you could also check the fan motor itself, but be warned, it's not as simple as just turning a knob. You might need to remove the fan assembly to get a good look at the motor. But if you're not comfortable doing it yourself, it's best to call a professional. And if you do decide to call a professional, make sure to find one who knows what they're doing and can give you a good estimate for the repair. Just remember, if you're not sure what you're doing, it's always better to call a professional than",
